</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,950,1733]" pageId="12" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1599,1625]" pageId="12" pageNumber="77">Remarks.</emphasis>
The smallest Indian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Solier" authorityYear="1833" box="[555,714,1599,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pheropsophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[555,714,1599,1625]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="77">Pheropsophus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
recorded. It is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arrow" authorityYear="1901" box="[1199,1343,1599,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Pheropsophus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricollis">
<emphasis box="[1199,1343,1599,1625]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="77">P. nigricollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but differs by having head bi-coloured with anterior yellow and posterior black, broad lateral bead of pronotum, obliterate humerus without spot, with median spot instead of median transverse band. Endemic to Eastern Himalaya hotspot of biodiversity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
